g.text: Here to There: A History of Mapping

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: From the 16th to 18th centuries, many European mapmakers were convinced that California was an island —

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: an Edenic paradise populated by black Amazons. The error persisted for over a hundred years after expeditions

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: had proven that California was, in fact, firmly attached to the mainland. The idea of California as a fierce

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: paradise appealed to Europeans, who were reluctant to let the mundane reality interfere with their vision of

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: the world. So in that spirit, we’re devoting this episode of BackStory to maps — asking what they show us

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: about who we are and and where we want to go. How do maps shape the way we see our communities and our

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: world? What do they tell us about the kind of information we value? And what do they distort, or ignore?

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: Please help us shape this show! Share your questions, ideas and stories below. Have opinions on New York

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: vs. D.C. subway maps? On the merits or shortcomings of Google Maps? And do you even still use

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: old-fashioned, ink-and-paper maps? Leave us a comment!
